00:05:13.760 --> 00:05:20.760
So I'd say, like, I think parquet files are superior to CSV files in just about every possible way.

00:05:20.799 --> 00:05:24.799
Except for one, and that's you can't open it in a text editor and look.

00:05:24.799 --> 00:05:30.799
And that's because it's a binary file format, which makes it much smaller and generally much faster.

00:05:30.799 --> 00:05:36.799
And the other big advantage to CSV files is that CSV files don't really have types of columns.

00:05:36.799 --> 00:05:41.799
Like, you can kind of figure out if it's a number or a string, but there's no real way to record, like,

00:05:41.799 --> 00:05:43.799
if it's a date or a date time or a factor.

00:05:43.799 --> 00:05:46.799
And parquet files have all of that.

00:05:46.839 --> 00:05:51.839
So what I do now, whenever I'm doing a data analysis, the first thing I do is create a parquet file.

00:05:51.839 --> 00:05:55.839
