But like, so when you do cluster analysis, right?

00:48:27.419 --> 00:48:28.939
You have to choose the number of clusters

00:48:28.939 --> 00:48:30.739
and there's a bunch of heuristics.

00:48:30.739 --> 00:48:32.619
But I think whenever you do cluster analysis,

00:48:32.619 --> 00:48:35.059
you want to do a little bit of experimenting.

00:48:35.059 --> 00:48:38.338
Like is my, are my results like robust

00:48:38.338 --> 00:48:40.258
to different numbers of clusters?

00:48:40.258 --> 00:48:42.539
And so what I did, I was like, okay, well,

00:48:43.179 --> 00:48:48.179
well, like make me a Shiny app that lets me explore that.

00:48:53.138 --> 00:48:55.299
This is one of my favorite uses for Shiny apps, y'all.

00:48:55.299 --> 00:48:57.138
I make apps all the time that let me step

00:48:57.138 --> 00:48:59.299
through something and look at it.

00:48:59.299 --> 00:49:01.138
Like one time I was doing a little project

00:49:01.138 --> 00:49:04.138
where I was classifying blue sky posts.

00:49:04.138 --> 00:49:07.299
And so I was like, I'm going to pre-classify these

00:49:07.299 --> 00:49:10.059
with an LLM and then I want to build a Shiny app

00:49:10.059 --> 00:49:12.378
and have the Shiny app feed me each one

00:49:13.218 --> 00:49:14.099
and tell me like what it had assigned it.

00:49:14.099 --> 00:49:16.739
And then I can decide whether or not it was something.

00:49:16.739 --> 00:49:19.818
I was trying to classify replies versus posts, basically

00:49:19.818 --> 00:49:22.698
just really basic stuff, just to see if I could do it.

00:49:22.698 --> 00:49:24.138
It was amazing.

00:49:24.138 --> 00:49:27.179
And like the ability to write like a Shiny app like this

00:49:27.179 --> 00:49:29.619
in like, you know, two or three minutes,

00:49:29.619 --> 00:49:30.818
this is really cool.

00:49:30.818 --> 00:49:33.099
Like, yes, I could have, I've, you know

00:49:33.099 --> 00:49:34.258
I could have written this Shiny app.

00:49:34.258 --> 00:49:36.179
I probably never would have before

00:49:36.179 --> 00:49:38.898
because I would have felt like the cost

00:49:38.898 --> 00:49:41.099
being a trade-off like wasn't there.

00:49:41.099 --> 00:49:43.458
But now like, just give it a go.

00:49:43.458 --> 00:49:46.698
And with an LLM, like it's not a super complicated

00:49:46.698 --> 00:49:49.338
Shiny app and that's fine.

00:49:49.338 --> 00:49:51.698
And it's a throwaway, so it doesn't have to be pretty.

00:49:51.698 --> 00:49:53.898
Just James Wade's talk at Pysoconf last year

00:49:53.898 --> 00:49:55.378
was about this, like throwaway Shiny apps.

00:49:55.378 --> 00:49:58.218
Why you should build them and throw them away.

00:49:58.218 --> 00:50:00.619
Yeah, and because the cost of like writing a bunch

00:50:00.619 --> 00:50:03.378
of R code is now much cheaper than it ever was before.

00:50:04.698 --> 00:50:05.539
Yeah, do it.

00:50:06.458 --> 00:50:09.218
And that reminds me of a question we got to earlier.

00:50:09.218 --> 00:50:11.018
We was asked earlier that I don't think I answered

00:50:11.898 --> 00:50:12.739
which is like, does it still make sense

00:50:12.739 --> 00:50:15.099
to learn how to code in 2026?

00:50:15.099 --> 00:50:16.659
Yeah, Ben had asked that again in the chat.

00:50:16.659 --> 00:50:18.778
Like, I want to hear Hadley's answer to that.

00:50:18.778 --> 00:50:21.258
And I want to say like, I think the,

00:50:23.979 --> 00:50:26.659
like, yes, I think understanding code

00:50:26.659 --> 00:50:28.138
is still really important.

00:50:29.138 --> 00:50:32.378
I do think the trade-off between the ability to read code

00:50:32.378 --> 00:50:34.419
and ability to write code has changed

00:50:34.419 --> 00:50:38.258
because now we can like generate so much code quickly

00:50:38.258 --> 00:50:39.099
with an LLM.

00:50:39.099 --> 00:50:41.898
Like your ability to read that code quickly,

00:50:41.898 --> 00:50:43.939
figure out, you know, understand what it's doing

00:50:43.939 --> 00:50:45.018
and if it's the right thing

00:50:45.018 --> 00:50:47.499
and then either like make small tweaks by hand

00:50:47.499 --> 00:50:49.458
or tell the LLM to fix it.

00:50:49.458 --> 00:50:52.338
But if you don't know what it's doing,

00:50:52.338 --> 00:50:56.659
that just seems like such a dangerous place to be in.

00:50:56.659 --> 00:51:00.939
Like if you don't have some sense of like,

00:51:00.939 --> 00:51:04.378
you know, you still, to do a good cluster analysis,

00:51:04.378 --> 00:51:05.859
you still need to understand like,

00:51:05.859 --> 00:51:09.299
oh, actually the number of clusters is really important.

00:51:09.299 --> 00:51:12.979
And, you know, we, there's no magic way

00:51:12.979 --> 00:51:15.378
to figure out the correct number of clusters.

00:51:15.378 --> 00:51:16.419
So you have to know,

00:51:16.419 --> 00:51:18.698
like the LLM will just give you some decent answer.

00:51:18.698 --> 00:51:21.739
You need to go to and like interrogate that further.

00:51:21.739 --> 00:51:24.619
So still that like subject matter knowledge,

00:51:24.619 --> 00:51:28.458
that ability to read code, that ability to like go in.

00:51:29.378 --> 00:51:31.539
Let's see if I can quickly switch back.

00:51:36.739 --> 00:51:40.859
You know, like you still want to create these data sets

00:51:40.859 --> 00:51:42.539
and the ability to like go in there

00:51:42.539 --> 00:51:47.539
and actually modify them directly is super important

00:51:47.539 --> 00:51:51.419
because, you know, being able to type a one

00:51:51.419 --> 00:51:52.339
instead of a two there,

00:51:52.339 --> 00:51:55.339
like that's much lower effort than saying to the LLM,

00:51:55.339 --> 00:51:57.539
hey, can you please go to this specific plot

00:51:57.539 --> 00:52:00.258
and do make this change for me?

00:52:00.258 --> 00:52:01.419
Like if you know exactly,

00:52:01.419 --> 00:52:03.138
like one of the advantages of doing this

00:52:03.738 --> 00:52:04.939
Like if you know exactly,

00:52:04.939 --> 00:52:08.459
like one of the advantages of code is that it's like,

00:52:08.459 --> 00:52:10.939
you know, it's this precise language

00:52:10.939 --> 00:52:15.219
and LLMs are great at going from your vague human language

00:52:15.219 --> 00:52:16.819
to this precise code language.

00:52:16.819 --> 00:52:17.819
But if you already know,

00:52:17.819 --> 00:52:19.978
if you already have that precision in mind,

00:52:19.978 --> 00:52:22.738
trying to tell an LLM what to do in human language

00:52:22.738 --> 00:52:24.618
to make a precise change,

00:52:24.618 --> 00:52:27.098
that's just like, that's inefficient.

00:52:27.098 --> 00:52:29.378
So I think like code is still important,

00:52:29.378 --> 00:52:31.258
but your ability to write code,

00:52:31.258 --> 00:52:33.819
I think is less important than it used to be.

00:52:33.819 --> 00:52:36.778
Your ability to read code is still more important

00:52:36.778 --> 00:52:40.138
and your ability to like ask good questions,

00:52:40.138 --> 00:52:42.459
like even, even more important.

00:52:42.459 --> 00:52:44.059
I will say we have two minutes left

00:52:44.059 --> 00:52:46.138
and I would love to end with just like a little,

