Like one of the things,

00:53:02.858 --> 00:53:05.339
like we're gonna have to learn new ways,

00:53:05.339 --> 00:53:07.339
to make new tools to, you know,

00:53:07.339 --> 00:53:09.419
new ways of doing this.

00:53:09.419 --> 00:53:10.539
I think one of the things

00:53:10.539 --> 00:53:12.339
that's always sort of intrigued me,

00:53:12.339 --> 00:53:15.098
I read this article, I don't know,

00:53:15.098 --> 00:53:16.618
like maybe 10 years ago

00:53:16.618 --> 00:53:21.618
about masters of fine arts in programming.

00:53:21.819 --> 00:53:22.858
And like, I don't know,

00:53:22.858 --> 00:53:24.858
I can't remember if it was like a real program

00:53:24.858 --> 00:53:26.299
or just kind of a speculation,

00:53:26.299 --> 00:53:27.378
but this idea like, you know,

00:53:27.378 --> 00:53:29.219
when you go and become an artist,

00:53:29.219 --> 00:53:30.858
you spend a bunch of time,

00:53:30.858 --> 00:53:33.059
obviously you do spend a bunch of time like making art,

00:53:33.059 --> 00:53:36.378
but also like looking at the work of like old masters

00:53:36.378 --> 00:53:38.098
and attempting to copy that by hand.

00:53:38.098 --> 00:53:39.699
And of course you could take a photograph

00:53:39.699 --> 00:53:41.059
of a famous painting

00:53:41.059 --> 00:53:43.339
that's gonna give you like an exact reproduction,

00:53:43.339 --> 00:53:47.018
but that recreating it by hand,

00:53:47.018 --> 00:53:50.498
you know, the things you do in like art and design programs

00:53:50.498 --> 00:53:53.219
where you like collectively talk through things,

00:53:53.219 --> 00:53:54.579
I think all of these skills,

00:53:54.579 --> 00:53:55.579
like we're gonna have to figure out

00:53:55.618 --> 00:53:57.738
how to apply them to the data science

00:53:57.738 --> 00:54:01.339
and programming today, like super duper important.

